master.notes: Coltrane's Ascension was originally released with the second take of the music from the recording session on June 28, 1965. These original pressings are commonly referred to as 'Edition I.' Shortly thereafter, Coltrane expressed a desire to instead use the first take. Impulse swapped out the stamper(s) for one(s) with the first take and inscribed 'Edition II' in the dead wax - ceasing production of the original version.Those recordings are grouped in another master release: [m=33212].If you have an orange/black labelled pressing of Ascension from the mid-to-late 1960s, the presence or absence of 'Edition II' in the dead wax is the simplest way to determine which version you have.The solo order differs slightly between the takes; Edition II also features no drum solo by Elvin Jones.Later CD issues have included both takes.
master.title: Ascension (Edition I)

master.notes: Coltrane's Ascension was originally released with the second take of the music from the recording session on June 28, 1965. These original pressings are commonly referred to as 'Edition I' and are grouped in a separate master release ([m=32364]. Shortly thereafter, Coltrane expressed a desire to instead use the first take. Impulse swapped out the stamper(s) for one(s) with the first take and inscribed 'Edition II' in the dead wax - ceasing production of the original version.If you have an orange/black labelled pressing of Ascension from the mid-to-late 1960s, the presence or absence of 'Edition II' in the dead wax is the simplest way to determine which version you have.The solo order differs slightly between the takes; Edition II also features no drum solo by Elvin Jones.Some later CD issues have included both takes.
master.title: Ascension (Edition II)

master.notes: The album's original release included tracks 1-7 listed below; "Aging" was included in Polydor's 2003 CD reissue of the album as a bonus track.The original album featured a distinctly jazz stereo mix with the drums in the right hand channel only, similar to Miles Davis's 1960s Quintet releases. The 1988 U.S. Polydor CD release featured a more rock-oriented mix with the drums centered, and bass and sax in the left and right channels respectively. The 2003 CD re-issue features the original jazz mix. While both mono and stereo versions of Things We Like were issued as promotional albums to U.S. radio stations in 1971, a mono version of the album has not been commercially issued. -Wikipedia
master.title: Things We Like

master.notes: "Coltrane Jazz" is the sixth studio album by jazz musician John Coltrane, released in 1961 on Atlantic Records, catalogue number SD 1354. The song "Village Blues" is noted as a landmark recording, as it marks the first session date of the early John Coltrane Quartet on record. Featured alongside Coltrane are pianist McCoy Tyner, drummer Elvin Jones, and bassist Steve Davis (who would within 18 months have been replaced by first Reggie Workman and then Jimmy Garrison who would stay with 'Trane until his death).
master.title: Coltrane Jazz

master.notes: This is the sound of independence, righteous and hot jump-up sounds from the 1950s and 60s, an exciting period of endless new musical styles that would travel across the world – Mento, the Jamaican precursor to reggae; mambos and descargas from Cuba, Dominican merengue, Haitian compas – and more.This album coincides with the release of Soul Jazz Records’ massive new deluxe large format hardback book 90 Degrees of Shade: 100 Years of Photography In The Caribbean (with foreward by Paul Gilroy) featuring hundreds of fascinating and unique photographs spanning one hundred years of Caribbean history.

master.notes: The UK release of Works Volume 1 (K 80009) had two different label layouts. Considering the left hand side of the labels, layout #1 had catalogue information in this order (Side A used as example): SIDE ONESTEREOK 80009 (bold text) (SD2-7000) K 80009 A Label layout #2 had a different order and made use of an asterisk. The fourth and fifth lines are indented:SIDE ONESTEREOK 80009 K 80009A* (SD 2-7000) In addition, the last publisher on side 3 switches between two lines on the asterisk version and one line on the non-asterisk version, and the publisher on side one has an additional comma - "Palm Beach International Recordings Ltd.," on asterisk labels.A copy could have all sides based on label layout #1, all sides based on label layout #2, or any combination of these.All versions of K 80009 will need to have the labels specified in the Notes.The UK release of Works Volume 1 also had at least two sets of etched handwriting on matrices, completely different to [url=http://www.discogs.com/release/7646094]one[/url] [url=http://www.discogs.com/release/7646372]another[/url], also coexisting in some discs. Hence, beyond combinations of label layouts, beyond combinations of matrices, there is also resulting combinations of both.
